# DESCRIPTION
# Gives a linear equation in the form ax + by = c and asks to find intercepts
# algebraically
# ENDDESCRIPTION

## DBsubject(Algebra)
## DBchapter(Linear equations and functions)
## DBsection(Graphs of lines)
## Institution(University of Missouri-Columbia)
## Author(Rick Lynch)
## Level(2)
## KEYWORDS('x-intercepts', 'y-intercepts', 'lines')

## Updated 2025.02 by Peter Staab, switch to PGML and add a solution


DOCUMENT();
loadMacros('PGstandard.pl', 'PGML.pl', 'contextFraction.pl', 'PGcourse.pl');

Context("LimitedFraction");
$A = non_zero_random(-20,20);
$B = non_zero_random(-20,20);
$C = non_zero_random(-20,20);

$x0 = Fraction($C,$A);
$y0 = Fraction($C,$B); 

Context(context::Fraction::extending("Point"));
$xint = Point($x0,0);
$yint = Point(0,$y0);

BEGIN_PGML
Find the [`x`]-intercept and [`y`]-intercept of the line: [` [$A]x+[$B]y=[$C] `]

a) [`x`]-intercept: [_]{$xint}

b) [`y`]-intercept: [_]{$yint}
END_PGML

BEGIN_PGML_SOLUTION
a)  The [`x`]-intercept is where the line crosses the [`x`]-axis or when [`y=0`].  Set this in the equation and solve for [`x`].
    [```
    \begin{aligned}
    [$A] x + 0 & = [$C] \\
    x & = \frac{[$C]}{[$A]} 
    \end{aligned}
    ```]

    Thus the [`x`]-intercept is [``[$xint]``].

b)  The [`y`]-intercept is where the line crosses the [`y`]-axis or when [`x=0`].  Set this in the equation and solve for [`y`].
    [```
    \begin{aligned}
    0 + [$B] y & = [$C] \\
    y & = \frac{[$C]}{[$B]}
    \end{aligned}
    ```]

    Thus the [`y`]-intercept is [``[$yint]``].

    
END_PGML_SOLUTION


COMMENT('determine intercepts of a linear function');
ENDDOCUMENT();